Machine learning (ML) is a branch of Artificial Intelligence that enables computers to learn patterns from data and improve their performance without being explicitly programmed for every task.

Instead of writing detailed rules for every situation, you provide the computer with examples (data), and it learns how to make predictions or decisions.

Simple example

Imagine you want a computer to recognize cats in photos.

Traditional programming: You would have to write rules such as "cats have pointy ears, whiskers, and four legs." This is difficult because cats vary in appearance.
Machine learning: You show the computer thousands of labeled cat and non-cat images. It learns the patterns that distinguish cats from other objects.

